{:proof/problem-id "apm-a94J03", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (continuous \\(f:\\mathbb R\\to\\mathbb R\\), open maps, strict monotonicity) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target concludes “strictly monotone” only after the continuity/open-map hypotheses) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (continuous open ⇒ monotone is a standard, self-contained theorem) · notes: the helper lemma isolates the key contradiction—non-monotone continuous functions have a local extremum, which breaks the open-map condition.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Show that a continuous open map f:ℝ→ℝ must be strictly monotone.\"\n :terms [{:name \"local extremum\"\n          :meaning \"If f is not monotone there exist x<y<z with f(y) ≥ max(f(x),f(z)) or ≤ min.\"\n          :needed-because \"Such a point witnesses failure of openness.\"}\n         {:name \"open map property\"\n          :meaning \"Images of open intervals must be open intervals.\"\n          :needed-because \"If f has a local extremum, the image of a symmetric interval is not open.\"}\n         {:name \"connectedness of intervals\"\n          :meaning \"Continuous images of intervals are intervals.\"\n          :needed-because \"Helps describe f((a,b)) as an interval with endpoints given by limits.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Non-monotone ⇒ existence of local extremum\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 local extremum description\"\n             :why-this-now \"Produce a point y where f takes a local maximum or minimum.\"\n             :lean-target \"nonmonotone_has_local_extremum\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Need lemma for continuous real functions.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Open image of intervals\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 open map property\"\n             :why-this-now \"Show that a local extremum contradicts openness.\"\n             :lean-target \"continuous_open_imp_monotone\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Lean already knows continuous images of intervals are intervals; need to prove boundary point contradiction.\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"A continuous open map f:ℝ→ℝ is strictly monotone (either strictly increasing or strictly decreasing).\"\n             :formal-name \"continuous_open_imp_monotone\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ f : ℝ → ℝ, Continuous f ∧ (∀ s, IsOpen s → IsOpen (f '' s)) → StrictMono f ∨ StrictAnti f\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Exactly restates the prelim claim.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"continuous_open_imp_monotone\"\n              :formal-statement \"∀ f : ℝ → ℝ, Continuous f ∧ (∀ s, IsOpen s → IsOpen (f '' s)) → StrictMono f ∨ StrictAnti f\"\n              :informal-clause \"Continuous open ⇒ monotone.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"nonmonotone_has_local_extremum\"\n              :formal-statement \"¬(StrictMono f ∨ StrictAnti f) → ∃ x, ∀ y near x, f y ≤ f x or f y ≥ f x\"\n              :informal-clause \"Finds the local extreme that violates openness.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (continuous \\(f:\\mathbb R\\to\\mathbb R\\), open-map hypothesis, strict monotonicity) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (monotonicity is only concluded after the continuity and open-image assumptions) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (continuous open ⇒ strictly monotone is a classic real-analysis fact) · notes: the helper lemma isolates the contradiction—if \\(f\\) isn’t monotone, continuity forces a local extremum that wrecks the open-map property.\n\n```\nP